kup and Imaging in Protocol Transitions\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Workup steps, such as physical examination, imaging for staging, PSA monitoring, and genetic testing, appear as pivotal transitions in several protocol pathways, most notably in initial staging (e.g., PROS-14, PROS-13, PROS-15) and during recurrence assessment (PROS-11). These steps are critical in determining appropriate therapy escalation or de-escalation and ensuring detection of metastatic or recurrent disease at clinically actionable timepoints. The recurrence and workup relationships highlight the importance of timely data collection and surveillance to support precision in subsequent clinical decisions [Data: Entities (38, 18, 40, 46, 37); Relationships (123, 108, 140, 38)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Therapeutic Decision Nodes Driven by Metastatic Disease Characterization\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Key protocol entities and relationships differentiate between synchronous and metachronous metastatic presentations, and further stratify by low- versus high-volume disease (PROS-13, PROS-14, PROS-15), each associated with specific treatment recommendations. For instance, in low-volume M1/synchronous oligometastatic castration-sensitive prostate cancer, options such as ADT with abiraterone, apalutamide, or enzalutamide are highlighted, whereas high-volume or synchronous/metachronous high-volume states prompt escalation to triplet therapies including docetaxel [Data: Entities (40, 37, 46, 42, 43, 47, 44, 48); Relationships (134, 135, 147, 127, 142)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Structured Management of Disease Recurrence and Progression\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Non-localized recurrences, such as biochemical recurrence after radiation or prostatectomy (PROS-10, PROS-9), trigger entry into next-step protocols like the workup for second biochemical recurrence (PROS-11) and eventual assessment and treatment of metastatic or castration-resistant states (PROS-17). This layered approach maintains continuity in guideline-recommended care and ensures that patients are re-staged and re-stratified as their disease biology evolves, with corresponding updates in therapeutic strategy [Data: Entities (0, 140, 18, 63, 45); Relationships (463, 0, 38, 180, 138)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Emphasis on Genetic Testing and Precision Medicine Principles\",\n      \"explanation\": \"In the workup sequence, protocols emphasize germline and somatic genetic testing to support tailored therapeutic decisions, highlighting the movement towards precision oncology in prostate cancer. For example, the use of agents such as niraparib/abiraterone in patients with BRCA2 mutations supports integration of genetic information into the NCCN pathway recommendations [Data: Entities (38, 44, 48); Relationships (123, 127, 142)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Clear Pathways for Escalation to Advanced and Castration-Resistant Disease Management\",\n      \"explanation\": \"As patients progress through initial, locally advanced, and metastatic protocols, explicit pathways lead into management of M1 castration-resistant prostate cancer (PROS-17), which is characterized by additional imaging and the consideration of alternative therapeutic agents. This ensures that advanced disease is managed with up-to-date evidence and maintains patient access to novel or combination treatments [Data: Entities (63, 41, 45); Relationships (180, 138, 115)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"All Protocol Entities Underpinned by Expected Patient Survival and Quality-of-Life Measures\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Across the community, expected patient survival and individualized assessment of life expectancy are used as guiding parameters at multiple decision nodes, ensuring that aggressiveness of intervention is suitable for patient context. Quality-of-life assessments remain integral throughout, reflecting the protocols’ commitment to balancing disease control with pat